---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../components/CodeExample.astro';
import HubCard from '../../../components/HubCard.astro';

const accessibilityUtilities = `.vh {}
.a11y-link {}
.a11y-link--focusable {}`;

const vhExample = `.vh {
    position: absolute;
    inline-size: 1px;
    block-size: 1px;
    overflow: hidden;
    clip-path: inset(50%);
    white-space: nowrap;
}`;

const skipLinkExample = `.a11y-link {
    position: absolute;
    inset-block-start: 0;
    inset-inline-start: 0;
    translate: 0 -100%;
}

.a11y-link--focusable:focus,
.a11y-link--focusable:focus-visible {
    translate: 0 0;
}`;

const avoidExample = `<article class="p-4 mb-4 bg-white rounded shadow text-center grid gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Product title</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-4">Product description</p>
</article>`;

const betterExample = `<article class="product-card">
    <h2 class="title">Product title</h2>
    <p class="description">Product description</p>
</article>`;

const decisionExample = `Ask:
Does this solve a universal accessibility problem?
→ Utility

Does this keep repeating as a UI pattern?
→ Component

Is this only visual presentation?
→ Theme or component, not utility`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Utilities"
    description="Utility classes in Layered Semantic CSS, including why most utilities should be avoided and where accessibility utilities are justified."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Apply</p>

        <h1>
            Utility classes
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Utilities should be rare helpers, not a second styling system hiding
            in your HTML. If utilities become the architecture, the architecture
            has quietly left the building.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Utilities sections">
        <a href="#rules">Decision rules</a>
        <a href="#accessibility-utilities">Accessibility utilities</a>
        <a href="#when-to-use">When to use one</a>
        <a href="#avoid">Avoid</a>
    </nav>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="rules">
            Quick decision rules
        </h2>

        <CodeExample code={decisionExample} language="text" />

        <p>
            A utility should have to justify its existence. Most spacing,
            layout, colour, and typography decisions belong in components,
            layout, or theme instead.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="accessibility-utilities">
            Accessibility utilities
        </h2>

        <p>
            These are the utilities that fit naturally because they solve
            universal browser and assistive technology problems, not temporary
            design decisions.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={accessibilityUtilities} />

        <h3>
            Visually hidden text
        </h3>

        <CodeExample code={vhExample} />

        <p>
            Use <code>.vh</code> for content that should remain available to
            screen readers while staying visually hidden.
        </p>

        <h3>
            Accessible jump links
        </h3>

        <CodeExample code={skipLinkExample} />

        <p>
            Use <code>.a11y-link</code> with
            <code>.a11y-link--focusable</code> for skip links that become visible
            when focused.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="when-to-use">
            When a utility is justified
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>It solves a universal accessibility problem.</li>
            <li>It behaves consistently across the whole project.</li>
            <li>It does not replace a meaningful component class.</li>
            <li>It stays understandable without requiring six companion utilities.</li>
            <li>It improves clarity instead of creating class soup.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            If the same utility group keeps appearing together, it is not a
            utility pattern. It is a component asking to be named.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="avoid">
            Avoid class soup
        </h2>

        <CodeExample code={avoidExample} language="html" />

        <p>
            This pushes layout, spacing, colour, and typography decisions into
            the markup and turns HTML into a styling spreadsheet.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={betterExample} language="html" />

        <p>
            Prefer semantic components when the markup represents a real UI
            pattern. Components scale. Utility soup spreads like ivy.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Next useful pages
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-grid">
            <HubCard href="/apply/architecture/" title="Architecture">
                <p>Decide when a repeated pattern should become a real component.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/apply/theme-layer/" title="Theme layer">
                <p>Move visual decisions into tokens and theme instead of utility chains.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/learn/anti-patterns/" title="Anti-patterns">
                <p>See how utility overload turns into class soup and hidden debt.</p>
            </HubCard>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
